-- Universal Generalization (Pi-Introduction)
--
-- Classical: If Gamma |- P(x) for arbitrary x, then Gamma |- forall x. P(x)
-- CredTT: lambda x. b : Pi x. B @ inf_x c(x)
--         Credence is INFIMUM over all instances
--
-- Example: Prove forall n. n + 0 = n
-- For each n, prove n + 0 = n at credence c(n)
-- Universal has credence inf{c(n) : n in Nat}

-- Classical universal: "for all x, P(x)" is true or false
-- CredTT universal: credence is infimum over instances

-- If every instance has credence >= 0.9, universal has >= 0.9
-- If ONE instance has credence 0.1, universal might have 0.1

-- Body of universal at uniform credence 1
postulate body : n_plus_0_eq_n @ 1

-- Universal generalization: credence = inf{1} = 1
derive forall_result : forall_n_plus_0_eq_n @ 1 from body by pi_intro

stable body
stable forall_result

-- Non-uniform credences:
-- Suppose P(0) @ 1, P(1) @ 1, P(2) @ 0.5, ...
-- Then forall n. P(n) @ inf{1, 1, 0.5, ...} = 0.5

-- This captures real uncertainty about universals:
-- "All swans are white" might be high credence
-- But one counterexample (black swan) drops credence

-- In CredTT, the universal is only as strong as
-- the weakest instance (infimum)

-- Dependent credences: c(x)
-- forall x. B(x) @ inf_x. c(x)
-- The credence DEPENDS on x

-- Example: confidence in P(n) might decrease with n
-- P(0) @ 1, P(1) @ 0.99, P(2) @ 0.98, ...
-- forall n. P(n) @ lim_{n->inf} c(n) = lim 0.99^n = 0
-- The universal has credence 0 even though each finite
-- instance has positive credence!

-- This is why CredTT can express things classical logic can't:
-- "We're confident in each instance but not the universal"
